article.headline: California 69, Oregon State 52
article.story: CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- California didn't take long to get redemption for last month's home loss to Oregon State. The Golden Bears opened the game with a 21-2 run and coasted to a 69-52 victory over the Beavers on Thursday night behind 16 points from Richard Midgley. "After that game we were down on ourselves," said Leon Powe, who had 13 points and 16 rebounds. "We let a team come in and get wide-open looks. That's not playing good defense." Ayinde Ubaka had 14 points and seven assists for the Golden Bears (13-6, 7-3 Pac-10). DeVon Hardin added seven points and seven rebounds. Sasa Cuic had 21 points and a career-high 11 rebounds to lead Oregon State, but Nick DeWitz and Chris Stephens were shut down for the second straight game. Cuic was the only Beaver in double-figures. The Beavers (10-11, 3-7) looked nothing like the team that beat Cal 72-64 at Haas Pavilion on Jan. 7, as they continue to struggle without point guard Lamar Hurd, who has missed five straight games with a groin injury. "The glue of the team is not with us," Beavers coach Jay John said. "We have come unglued." John made his frustration felt early in the game, yanking all five of his starters with his team down 8-0 early. It didn't get any better from there as California built a 21-2 lead. Midgley scored eight quick points for Cal and the Beavers missed 11 of their first 12 shots. Oregon State's offense slowly came around, but the State still carried a comfortable 39-26 lead into halftime. The Bears have won three in a row and are tied for second in the conference, one game behind UCLA. Cal outrebounded the Beavers 43-21 and held them to a season-low 32 percent from the field. Keeping that going down the stretch could help propel the team into the NCAA tournament, particularly since the Bears have the lowest turnover ratio in the conference. "When you defend you have a chance," Cal coach Ben Braun said. "I've said it, I've said it, and I've said it. We have a chance and its great to see our guys believe on the defensive end." Powe, the conference's second-leading scorer and top rebounder, tallied his sixth consecutive double-double and 10th on the year. DeWitz finished with two points, nine off his season average, and Stephens, the Beavers' leading scorer at 14 per game, had five points. John, who kept the Beavers off-limits to the media after game, went to his bench often, playing freshman Brett Casey 20 minutes at point guard over two more established players, Jason Fontenet and Wesley Washington. "Three weeks ago, I finally became comfortable with a rotation of eight guys, who could play on both offense and defense," John said. "Right now we don't have that on offense and we don't have it on defense."
